<article>
    <h1>Be open to new ways of man&#xAD;ag&#xAD;ing road traf&#xAD;fic</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20200718/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-07-18"><time>2020-07-18</time></a>
        - <span>SCIENCE</span>
        - <span role="byline">Ng Kei Yong</span>
    </section>

    <p>I took a drive down­town yes­ter­day and was sur­prised that de­spite there be­ing no Elec­tronic Road Pric­ing charges, the roads were not con­gested.</p>
    <p>In fact, traf­fic was flow­ing smoothly.</p>
    <p>I think a big rea­son for this is that many peo­ple are still work­ing from home.</p>
    <p>This is a good op­por­tu­nity for the au­thor­i­ties to ex­plore traf­fic man­age­ment mea­sures other than those they have been re­ly­ing on for years, in which mo­torists pay for us­ing the roads at var­i­ous lo­ca­tions and at var­i­ous times of the day.</p>
    <p>If yes­ter­day’s road con­di­tions are any in­di­ca­tion, work­ing from home and stag­gered work­ing hours seem more ef­fec­tive at man­ag­ing road use.</p>


